                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5231/727: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Spain (<persName corresp="#p_WJC1" type="from"
                            >Wiley</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-27T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >June 27, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>57. Referring to the Embassy’s telegram No. 36, May 6, 5 p.m., a group of local
                    representatives of American tire companies have called on the Commercial
                    Attaché. They informed him that the Ministry of State has told them that the
                    only question which was holding up the granting of most-favored-nation treatment
                    by Spain <pb facs="0644" n="554" xml:id="pg_554"/> to American products was the
                    nonreceipt of a reply to the Spanish note of May 5 requesting an amplification
                    of the list transmitted with the Embassy’s note of April 23.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
